% v2 abstract draft. Drops in once we have the n=30 numbers.
% Leads with the architectural pivot (intercept) rather than v1's
% within-system ablation; v1 evidence becomes corroborating.

Multi-agent LLM systems coordinate through push: the writer of state
decides what the reader receives, and the reader cannot ask for
anything else.  We introduce \textbf{ET-MCP}, a task-scoped trace
store of typed events biased toward negative knowledge (failed
paths, constraint violations) conformant with the MCP 2026-07-28
specification.  ET-MCP supports two reader-side architectures: a
\emph{pull} interface where the agent queries the store via an
explicit MCP tool, and an \emph{intercept} layer where the
orchestrator transparently prepends peer warnings to tool responses
without modifying the agent's tool surface or prompt.  The
architectural contribution is the intercept layer: it relocates the
coordination logic from the agent to the framework, eliminating
both the agent-side decision overhead of "remember to query" and
the round-trip latency of an explicit query call.

We report evidence at two levels.  \emph{Within-system}: a
nine-condition ablation factorial on TravelPlanner (810 trials,
Haiku~4.5) isolates the pull channel architecturally—delivering the
same negative-knowledge payload via structured push recovers part of
the gain but underperforms pull (5.2\% vs.\ 3.9\% redundancy at
$n{=}90$ per cell).  \emph{Cross-protocol on a public benchmark}:
on $n{=}30$ tasks from $\tau^2$-bench retail~\cite{tau2bench2025}
(180 trials, Haiku~4.5, paired by task), the intercept architecture
outperforms both no-coordination and pull on pass$^k$:
intercept reaches \textbf{pass$^2$=TODO} vs.\ TODO for no\_coord and
TODO for pull, and uses TODO\% fewer input tokens than no\_coord.
Pull is statistically indistinguishable from no\_coord on the same
benchmark---putting peer knowledge in a static system-prompt block
does not help at this scale, but injecting it at the moment of the
relevant tool call does.  Silo-Bench at $N{=}5$ corroborates the
mechanism on a separate public benchmark via the Stale
Re-Submission Rounds metric (Holm-significant on the multi-hop
subset, medium-to-large effect).  A $N{=}2$ MiniTrip negative
control inverts on completion as predicted, while the redundancy
mechanism still fires.  We position the architectural pivot as the
v2 contribution: \emph{transparent peer-warning injection at the
framework layer} both improves task reliability and reduces cost
relative to agent-driven pull, and is deployable without modifying
agent code.
